1. Problem Statement

In today’s competitive market, businesses need to understand their customers better to improve sales and customer satisfaction. However, large amounts of customer data make it difficult to identify meaningful patterns manually.
This project aims to group customers into different segments based on their behavior and spending patterns, helping businesses make smarter marketing decisions.

2. Dataset

The project uses the Mall Customer Segmentation Dataset, which contains details such as:

Customer ID
Gender
Age
Annual Income
Spending Score

This dataset helps in analyzing customer behavior and identifying different groups.

3. Algorithm Used

The main algorithm used is:

K-Means Clustering
An unsupervised machine learning algorithm
Groups data into K clusters based on similarity
Works by:
Choosing number of clusters (K)
Assigning points to nearest cluster center
Updating cluster centers (centroids)
Repeating until convergence

We may also use:

Elbow Method → to find optimal number of clusters
4. Methodology (Steps)
Import dataset using Python (Pandas)
Perform data preprocessing
Select important features (Income, Spending Score)
Use Elbow Method to find optimal K
Apply K-Means clustering
Visualize clusters using graphs (Matplotlib/Seaborn)
Interpret customer groups
5. Expected Output
Customers divided into distinct groups, such as:
High income – high spending (target customers)
High income – low spending
Low income – high spending
Low income – low spending
Graphical visualization of clusters
Insights for business decision-making
6. Tools & Technologies
Python
Pandas
NumPy
Matplotlib / Seaborn
Scikit-learn
7. Conclusion

This project will help understand customer behavior and enable businesses to design targeted marketing strategies. It demonstrates the practical use of machine learning in real-world business problems.